UPDATE procedures SET body_md_source_text = 'Warning!

 Always follow national legislation and guidelines, and manufacturer-specific safety regulations, when working on high-voltage systems

 Warning: Risk of electrocution

 Caution! Personnel with implanted medical devices should not work on high-voltage systems due to the risk of device malfunction/failure

 Caution! Take the following precautions before commencing work on the high-voltage system:

 • Work on high-voltage systems should only be carried out by trained technicians

 • Erect safety barriers to mark the working area when deactivating the high-voltage circuit

 • Remove all metal objects such as rings and watches

 • When working on the high-voltage system, suitable tools and equipment must be used

 Note: Wear high-voltage insulating gloves with a minimum rating of class 0 (1000V)

 Caution! Always check the personal protective equipment (PPE) and the high-voltage insulating gloves for damage before working on high-voltage systems

 ZEnlarge

 • Wear a face shield eye protection approved for working on high-voltage systems

 • Wear approved dielectric overboots or approved footwear while working on high-voltage systems

 • (Electrically Insulating Footwear EN 50321 Class 0/Dielectric Footwear ASTM F1117)

 • The high-voltage cables are usually coloured orange

 Caution! While servicing the vehicle, do not charge the batteries

 Service battery - working guidelines:

 Note: Before disconnecting the 12V power supply, ensure that the driver’s door window is fully open

 Warning: If the 12V power supply is disconnected, do not attempt to open the doors with the door glass in the closed position

 Failure to follow this instruction could result in the door glass shattering

 Failure to follow this instruction could result in vehicle lockout

 General

 Prevent accidental vehicle activation by storing all keys/key fobs securely outside the working area

 Attach high-voltage warning labels at the front and rear of the vehicle

 Note: High-voltage work should be supervised by a qualified senior technician

 De-energising

 Erect safety barriers to mark the working area when deactivating the high-voltage circuit

 Disconnect the high-voltage battery charger cable

 Disconnect and remove all the 12V battery chargers

 Connect the diagnostic tool

 • Select ''ODIS-Service''

 • Select ''Special Functions''

 • Select ''High-voltage''

 • Select ''0051 - High-voltage power disconnect''

 Follow the instructions on the screen of the diagnostic tool

 Open the bonnet

 Warning: Wear appropriate personal protective equipment (PPE) and high-voltage insulating gloves to carry out the rest of this procedure

 Note: Also wear leather outer gloves

 Pull the securing clip outwards (1)

 Press the securing clip downwards (2)

 ZEnlarge

 Disconnect the high-voltage service connector

 ZEnlarge

 Warning: Do not remove the high-voltage connector

 Lock the high-voltage service connector 

 (

 T40262/1

 )

 ZEnlarge

 Keep the padlock key outside the vehicle

 Check for any residual voltage in the high-voltage system

 The procedure is complete when the high-voltage system status is confirmed as de-energised

 Re-energising

 Connect the diagnostic tool

 • Select ''ODIS-Service''

 • Select ''Special Functions''

 • Select ''High-voltage''

 • Select ''0051 - High-voltage restart''

 Follow the instructions on the screen of the diagnostic tool

 Warning: Wear appropriate personal protective equipment (PPE) and high-voltage insulating gloves to carry out the rest of this procedure

 Note: Also wear leather outer gloves

 Remove the padlock 

 (

 T40262/1

 )

 ZEnlarge

 Reconnect the high-voltage service connector (1->2->3)

